 <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 italic"><strong>"The factory looked perfect on Alibaba. Gold supplier. Five years in business. Verified badge. I sent $28,000 and waited."</strong></p>
 <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mt-4">That was David, a UK-based brand owner. He learned the hard way that a polished Alibaba profile doesn't mean a real factory exists. His supplier was a trading company with no production line. By the time he found out, his deposit was gone and his launch was delayed by four months.</p>
 <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mt-4">David's mistake is one of the most common, and most expensive, in China sourcing. The good news: it's entirely preventable with the right verification process. This guide walks you through factory verification, OEM/ODM negotiation, and the red flags that separate legitimate manufacturers from the rest.</p>
 <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mt-4">According to a 2024 Alibaba supplier quality report, only <strong>12% of electronics suppliers</strong> on B2B platforms pass comprehensive third-party factory audits (<a href="https://www.alibaba.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-brandBlue hover:text-brandOrange">Alibaba Supplier Insights</a>), making independent verification a non-negotiable step before committing any order. Industry-wide, <strong>41% of factories inspected in China</strong> failed quality and/or compliance checks (QIMA 2024 data), while approximately 30% of China-origin shipments fail independent AQL quality inspection.</p>
 <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mt-4">The stakes are high: in December 2025, the DOJ announced the <strong>largest customs fraud settlement in False Claims Act history ($54.4 million)</strong> for transshipping Chinese goods, signaling that enforcement on China origin fraud is escalating sharply. According to <a href="https://www.ibisworld.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-brandBlue hover:text-brandOrange">IBISWorld</a>, the global electronics OEM/ODM market is estimated at $280 billion, with China-based manufacturers representing approximately 65% of total production capacity.</p>
