 <section id="quality" class="mb-16">
 <h2 class="text-2xl font-black text-brandBlue uppercase italic mb-4">5. Quality Control & Testing</h2>
 <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Quality control is what separates reliable manufacturers from inconsistent suppliers. Ensure your supplier has a documented QC process with clear checkpoints at every production stage:</p>
 <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 text-slate-600 mb-4">
 <li><strong>IQC</strong>, Incoming component inspection (cells, ICs, PCBs)</li>
 <li><strong>IPQC</strong>, In-process monitoring during assembly</li>
 <li><strong>FQC</strong>, Final functional testing (charging speed, safety cut-off, cycle life)</li>
 <li><strong>OQC</strong>, Outgoing quality check before shipment</li>
 <li><strong>Aging test</strong>, -hour burn-in test to catch early failures</li>
 </ul>
 <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">Ask your supplier for their QC checklist and sample test reports. Manufacturers with ISO 9001 certification follow these processes by default. Requesting photos or video of each QC stage during production is a reasonable request that legitimate manufacturers accommodate regularly.</p>
 <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mt-4">The difference between a factory that performs 100% testing and one that uses statistical sampling is significant. Manufacturers like WOWOHCOOL that conduct 4-hour full-load burn-in testing on every single unit can document defect rates below 0.3%, while sample-based testing allows defective units to reach customers. Always ask about the testing percentage during supplier evaluation.</p>
